## Migration: `EventProcessor` → .NET 8

### Problems in the Original Code

| API | Issue on .NET 8 |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Unreliable, obsolete in .NET 9 (SYSLIB0046) |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Can't be woken by cancellation token |
| Race condition | Multiple enqueues with one `Reset()` can lose signals |

### Patterns Identified

1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while(true)` with blocking wait
2. **Blocking call interruption** — `Thread.Interrupt()` to wake `WaitOne()`
3. **Uncooperative termination** — `Thread.Abort()` as fallback

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _task;

    public void Start()
    {
        _task = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — exit gracefully
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();      // Signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // Timeout fallback

        if (_task is not null)
            await _task;
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

---

### If You Need a Synchronous API

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();           // Preferred: drain naturally
        if (!_thread?.Join(5000) ?? false)
            _cts.Cancel();                 // Force exit after timeout
        _thread?.Join(1000);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls to Avoid

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| Expecting `Cancel()` to instantly stop `Handle()` | Pass `CancellationToken` into `Handle` and check it at safe points |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Implement `IDisposable`; wrap in `using` at call site |
| Original race condition (multiple enqueues, one signal) | `Channel<T>` and `BlockingCollection<T>` are inherently race-free |
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` mid-chain | Only catch at the top-level loop; let it propagate otherwise |
| Not calling `CompleteAdding()`/`Writer.Complete()` | Without this, `ReadAllAsync`/`GetConsumingEnumerable` blocks forever |

---

### Why `Channel<T>` is Preferred

- Lock-free, high-throughput producer/consumer
- Native `CancellationToken` support on reads
- `ReadAllAsync` + `await foreach` = clean shutdown semantics
- No manual `WaitHandle` or `lock` needed

The `Channel<T>` version (first example) is the idiomatic .NET 8 approach. Use the `BlockingCollection<T>` version only if you must keep synchronous threading (e.g., interop constraints).
